  EFF leader Julius Malema arriving at the party's sixth-anniversary celebrations at the KaNyamazane Stadium in Nelspruit. Video: Loyiso Sidimba
 

 He said the ANC and the municipality it governs were scared of Rupert.
 "Let us go there. The leadership of the EFF will announce the date and time, the targeted properties of Rupert where we are going to visit peacefully and say to him 'if you want to voetsek, voetsek, stop threatening us here," Malema explained. 
He said if Rupert wants to leave the country he must do so.

 It was recently reported that Rupert was considering leaving South Africa because of his disappointment with the ANC, Ramaphosa and the possibility of Deputy President David Mabuza becoming the head of state.
